from them. Commercial trading of cloth is also the subject of a study of fifteenth-century brokers' books, revealing details of types, designs, and regulation of the famous silks from Lucca, Italy. Another paper focuseson art, reconsidering the incidence of frilled veils in the Low Countries and adopting an innovative means of analysis to question the chronology, geographical diversity, and social context of this style. Robin Netherton is a professional editor and a researcher/lecturer on the interpretation of medieval European dress; Gale R. Owen-Crocker is Professor of Anglo-Saxon Culture at the University of Manchester. Contributors: Benjamin L.Wild, Isis Sturtewagen, Kimberly Jack, Mark Chambers, Eleanor Quinton, John Oldland, Christine Meek  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aClothing and dressxHistoryyMedieval, 500-1500. 0aTextile fabrics, Medieval. 4aArchaeology & Heritage. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aDESIGN / Textile & Costume.2bisacsh  aMedieval reenactment.  aMedieval reenactors.1 aChambers, Mark C, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChambers, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJack, Kimberly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeek, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNetherton, Robin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOldland, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOwen-Crocker, Gale R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aQuinton, Eleanor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSturtewagen, Isis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWild, Benjamin L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l